# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gnmi-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] gRPC uses HTTP/2 for transport, Protocol Buffers as the interface description language, and provides features such as authentication, bidirectional streaming and flow control, blocking or nonblocking bindings, and cancellation and timeouts.
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] It generates cross-platform client and server bindings for many languages.
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] The most common usage scenarios include connecting services in a microservices style architecture, or connecting mobile device clients to backend services.
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] gRPC's use of HTTP trailers makes it impossible to implement a gRPC client in a browser, instead requiring a proxy.
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] From about 2001, Google created a general-purpose RPC infrastructure called Stubby to connect the large number of microservices running within and across its data centers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] In March 2015, Google decided to build the next version of Stubby and make it open source.
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] gRPC supports the usage of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and token-based authentication.
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] Connection to Google services must use TLS.
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] There are two types of credentials: channel credentials and call credentials.
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] For token-based authorization, gRPC provides Server Interceptor and a Client Interceptor.
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] gRPC uses Protocol Buffers to encode data.
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] Protocol buffers provide a serialization format and an interface definition language.
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] Some of the software tools used for testing gRPC implementations include Postman, ezy, Insomnia, and Step CI.
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] Many organizations use gRPC, including Uber, Square, Netflix, IBM, CoreOS, Docker, CockroachDB, Arista Networks, Cisco, Juniper Networks, Spotify, Zalando, Dropbox, and Google as the original developer.
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] The open source project u-bmc uses gRPC to replace Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).
[src:gnmi-protocol/grpc] On 8 January 2019, Dropbox announced that the next version of "Courier", their RPC framework at the core of their service-oriented architecture (SOA), would be migrated to be based on gRPC, primarily because it aligned well with their existing custom RPC frameworks.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:gnmi-protocol/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] Google developed Protocol Buffers for internal use and provided a code generator for multiple languages under an open-source license.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] The design goals for Protocol Buffers emphasized simplicity and performance.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] In particular, it was designed to be smaller and faster than XML.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is widely used at Google for storing and interchanging all kinds of structured information.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] The method serves as a basis for a custom remote procedure call (RPC) system that is used for nearly all inter-machine communication at Google.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is similar to the Apache Thrift, Amazon Ion, and Microsoft Bond protocols, offering a concrete RPC protocol stack to use for defined services called gRPC.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] Data structure schemas (called *messages*) and services are described in a proto definition file (`.proto`) and compiled with `protoc`.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] This compilation generates code that can be invoked by a sender or recipient of these data structures.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] For example, `example.pb.cc` and `example.pb.h` are generated from `example.proto`.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] They define C++ classes for each message and service in `example.proto`.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] Canonically, messages are serialized into a binary wire format which is compact, forward- and backward-compatible, but not self-describing (that is, there is no way to tell the names, meaning, or full datatypes of fields without an external specification).
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] There is no defined way to include or refer to such an external specification (schema) within a Protocol Buffers file.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] The officially supported implementation includes an ASCII serialization format, but this format—though self-describing—loses the forward- and backward-compatibility behavior, and is thus not a good choice for applications other than human editing and debugging.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] Though the primary purpose of Protocol Buffers is to facilitate network communication, its simplicity and speed make Protocol Buffers an alternative to data-centric C++ classes and structs, especially where interoperability with other languages or systems might be needed in the future.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] The format is best suited for small data chunks that don't exceed a few megabytes and can be loaded/sent into memory right away and therefore is not a streamable format.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] The library doesn't provide compression out of the box.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] The format also isn't well supported in non–object-oriented languages (e.g.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] A schema for a particular use of protocol buffers associates data types with field names, using integers to identify each field.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] The `Point` message defines two mandatory data items, `x` and `y`.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] The tag is defined after the equal sign.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] The `Line` and `Polyline` messages, which both use `Point`, demonstrate how composition works in Protocol Buffers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] `Polyline` has a `repeated` field, and thus `Polyline` behaves like a set of points (of unspecified number).
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] This schema can subsequently be compiled for use by one or more programming languages.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] Google provides a compiler called `protoc` which can produce output for C++, Java or Python.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] Other schema compilers are available from other sources to create language-dependent output for over 20 other languages.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 2.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java, C#, and Python.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 3.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java (including JavaNano, a dialect intended for low-resource environments), Kotlin, Python, Go, Ruby, Objective-C, C#, PHP, Dart.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] It also supports JavaScript since 3.0.0-beta-2.
[src:gnmi-protocol/protocol-buffers] Third-party implementations are also available for Ada, Ballerina, C, C++, Dart, Elixir, Erlang, Haskell, JavaScript, Julia, Nim, Perl, PHP, Prolog, R, Rust, Scala, and Swift.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] That is, the programmer writes essentially the same code whether the subroutine is local to the executing program, or remote.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] This is a form of server interaction (caller is client, executor is server), typically implemented via a request–response message passing system.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] In the object-oriented programming paradigm, RPCs are represented by remote method invocation (RMI).
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The RPC model implies a level of location transparency, namely that calling procedures are largely the same whether they are local or remote, but usually, they are not identical, so local calls can be distinguished from remote calls.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Remote calls are usually orders of magnitude slower and less reliable than local calls, so distinguishing them is important.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Many different (often incompatible) technologies have been used to implement the concept.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Request–response protocols date to early distributed computing in the late 1960s, theoretical proposals of remote procedure calls as the model of network operations date to the 1970s, and practical implementations date to the early 1980s.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Bruce Jay Nelson is generally credited with coining the term "remote procedure call" in 1981.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Remote procedure calls used in modern operating systems trace their roots back to the RC 4000 multiprogramming system, which used a request-response communication protocol for process synchronization.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The idea of treating network operations as remote procedure calls goes back at least to the 1970s in early ARPANET documents.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] In 1978, Per Brinch Hansen proposed Distributed Processes, a language for distributed computing based on "external requests" consisting of procedure calls between processes.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] One of the earliest practical implementations was in 1982 by Brian Randell and colleagues for their Newcastle Connection between UNIX machines.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] This was soon followed by "Lupine" by Andrew Birrell and Bruce Nelson in the Cedar environment at Xerox PARC.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Lupine automatically generated stubs, providing type-safe bindings, and used an efficient protocol for communication.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] One of the first business uses of RPC was by Xerox under the name "Courier" in 1981.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The first popular implementation of RPC on Unix was Sun's RPC (now called ONC RPC), used as the basis for Network File System (NFS).
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] In the 1990s, with the popularity of object-oriented programming, an alternative model of remote method invocation (RMI) was widely implemented, such as in Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA, 1991) and Java remote method invocation.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] RMIs, in turn, fell in popularity with the rise of the internet, particularly in the 2000s.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] An RPC is initiated by the *client*, which sends a request message to a known remote *server* to execute a specified procedure with supplied parameters.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The remote server sends a response to the client, and the application continues its process.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] While the server is processing the call, the client is blocked (it waits until the server has finished processing before resuming execution), unless the client sends an asynchronous request to the server, such as an XMLHttpRequest.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] There are many variations and subtleties in various implementations, resulting in a variety of different (incompatible) RPC protocols.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] An important difference between remote procedure calls and local calls is that remote calls can fail because of unpredictable network problems.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Also, callers generally must deal with such failures without knowing whether the remote procedure was actually invoked.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Idempotent procedures (those that have no additional effects if called more than once) are easily handled, but enough difficulties remain that code to call remote procedures is often confined to carefully written low-level subsystems.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The client stub packs the parameters into a message and makes a system call to send the message.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Packing the parameters is called marshalling.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The client's local operating system sends the message from the client machine to the server machine.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The local operating system on the server machine passes the incoming packets to the server stub.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The server stub unpacks the parameters from the message.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Unpacking the parameters is called unmarshalling.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Finally, the server stub calls the server procedure.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The reply traces the same steps in the reverse direction.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] To let different clients access servers, a number of standardized RPC systems have been created.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Most of these use an interface description language (IDL) to let various platforms call the RPC.
[src:gnmi-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The IDL files can then be used to generate code to interface between the client and servers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Although the term commonly refers to wireless data transfer mechanisms (e.g., using radio, ultrasonic, or infrared systems), it also encompasses data transferred over other media such as a telephone or computer network, optical link or other wired communications like power line carriers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Many modern telemetry systems take advantage of the low cost and ubiquity of GSM networks by using SMS to receive and transmit telemetry data.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] A *telemeter* is a physical device used in telemetry.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] It consists of a sensor, a transmission path, and a display, recording, or control device.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Electronic devices are widely used in telemetry and can be wireless or hard-wired, analog or digital.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Other technologies are also possible, such as mechanical, hydraulic and optical.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry may be commutated to allow the transmission of multiple data streams in a fixed frame.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] The beginning of industrial telemetry lies in the steam age, although the sensor was not called *telemeter* at that time.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Examples are James Watt's (1736-1819) additions to his steam engines for monitoring from a (near) distance such as the mercury pressure gauge and the fly-ball governor.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In 1889 this led an author in the Institution of Civil Engineers proceedings to suggest that the term for the rangefinder telemeter might be replaced with tacheometer.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In the 1930s use of electrical telemeters grew rapidly.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] The electrical strain gauge was widely used in rocket and aviation research and the radiosonde was invented for meteorological measurements.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] The advent of World War II gave an impetus to industrial development and henceforth many of these telemeters became commercially viable.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Carrying on from rocket research, radio telemetry was used routinely as space exploration got underway.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Spacecraft are in a place where a physical connection is not possible, leaving radio or other electromagnetic waves (such as infrared lasers) as the only viable option for telemetry.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] During crewed space missions it is used to monitor not only parameters of the vehicle, but also the health and life support of the astronauts.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] During the Cold War telemetry found uses in espionage.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] US intelligence found that they could monitor the telemetry from Soviet missile tests by building a telemeter of their own to intercept the radio signals and hence learn a great deal about Soviet capabilities.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemeters are the physical devices used in telemetry.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetering information over wire had its origins in the 19th century.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] One of the first data-transmission circuits was developed in 1845 between the Russian Tsar's Winter Palace and army headquarters.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In 1874, French engineers built a system of weather and snow-depth sensors on Mont Blanc that transmitted real-time information to Paris.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Michalke patented the selsyn, a circuit for sending synchronized rotation information over a distance.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In 1906 a set of seismic stations were built with telemetering to the Pulkovo Observatory in Russia.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In 1912, Commonwealth Edison developed a system of telemetry to monitor electrical loads on its power grid.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] The Panama Canal (completed 1913–1914) used extensive telemetry systems to monitor locks and water levels.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Wireless telemetry made early appearances in the radiosonde, developed concurrently in 1930 by Robert Bureau in France and Pavel Molchanov in Russia.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Molchanov's system modulated temperature and pressure measurements by converting them to wireless Morse code.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] The German V-2 rocket used a system of primitive multiplexed radio signals called "Messina" to report four rocket parameters, but it was so unreliable that Wernher von Braun once claimed it was more useful to watch the rocket through binoculars.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In the US and the USSR, the Messina system was quickly replaced with better systems; in both cases, based on pulse-position modulation (PPM).
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Early Soviet missile and space telemetry systems which were developed in the late 1940s used either PPM (e.g., the Tral telemetry system developed by OKB-MEI) or pulse-duration modulation (e.g., the RTS-5 system developed by NII-885).
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In the United States, early work employed similar systems, but were later replaced by pulse-code modulation (PCM) (for example, in the Mars probe Mariner 4).
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Later Soviet interplanetary probes used redundant radio systems, transmitting telemetry by PCM on a decimeter band and PPM on a centimeter band.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Although the two terms are closely related, telemetry and telematics are used differently depending on the field.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telematics, by contrast, emerged later as a broader, more applied concept that combines telemetry with telecommunications, informatics, and digital fleet platforms.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In short, telemetry is the enabling technology (remote measurement and data transmission), while telematics describes the integrated, digitalized applications that build on telemetry to deliver business, safety, and operational insights.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Weather balloons use telemetry to transmit meteorological data since 1920.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry is used to transmit drilling mechanics and formation evaluation information uphole, in real time, as a well is drilled.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] These services are known as Measurement while drilling and Logging while drilling.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Information acquired thousands of feet below ground, while drilling, is sent through the drilling hole to the surface sensors and the demodulation software.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] The pressure wave (sana) is translated into useful information after DSP and noise filters.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] This information is used for Formation evaluation, Drilling Optimization, and Geosteering.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry is used in modern motor racing, allowing race engineers to interpret data collected during a test or race and use it to properly tune the car for optimum performance.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Systems used in series such as Formula One have become advanced to the point where the potential lap time of the car can be calculated, and this time is what the driver is expected to meet.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Examples of measurements on a race car include accelerations (G forces) in three axes, temperature readings, wheel speed, and suspension displacement.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In Formula One, driver input is also recorded so the team can assess driver performance and (in case of an accident) the FIA can determine or rule out driver error as a possible cause.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Later developments include two-way telemetry which allows engineers to update calibrations on the car in real time (even while it is out on the track).
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In Formula One, two-way telemetry surfaced in the early 1990s and consisted of a message display on the dashboard which the team could update.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Its development continued until May 2001, when it was first allowed on the cars.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] By 2002, teams were able to change engine mapping and deactivate engine sensors from the pit while the car was on the track.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] For the 2003 season, the FIA banned two-way telemetry from Formula One; however, the technology may be used in other types of racing or on road cars.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] One way telemetry system has also been applied in R/C racing car to get information by car's sensors like: engine RPM, voltage, temperatures, throttle.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In the transportation industry, a Fleet telematics system is used to provide information about a vehicle or driver's performance by collecting data from on-board sensors, such as a GPS tracking unit or a telematics control unit (TCU).
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] This is undertaken for various reasons ranging from staff compliance monitoring, insurance rating, fuel management to predictive maintenance.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] As part of an Intelligent transportation system, telemetry is used to link traffic counter devices to data recorders to measure traffic flows and vehicle lengths and weights.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry is used by the railway industry for measuring the health of trackage.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] This permits optimized and focused predictive and preventative maintenance.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Typically this is done with specialized trains, such as the New Measurement Train used in the United Kingdom by Network Rail, which can check for track defects, such as problems with gauge, and deformations in the rail.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Japan uses similar, but quicker trains, nicknamed Doctor Yellow.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Such trains, besides checking the tracks, can also verify whether or not there are any problems with the overhead power supply (catenary), where it is installed.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Dedicated rail inspection companies, such as Sperry Rail, have their own customized rail cars and rail-wheel equipped trucks, that use a variety of methods, including lasers, ultrasound, and induction (measuring resulting magnetic fields from running electricity into rails) to find any defects.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Most activities related to healthy crops and good yields depend on timely availability of weather and soil data.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Therefore, wireless weather stations play a major role in disease prevention and precision irrigation.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Because local micro-climates can vary significantly, such data needs to come from within the crop.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Monitoring stations usually transmit data back by terrestrial radio, although occasionally satellite systems are used.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Solar power is often employed to make the station independent of the power grid.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry is used in water management, including water quality and stream gauging functions.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Major applications include AMR (automatic meter reading), groundwater monitoring, leak detection in distribution pipelines and equipment surveillance.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Having data available in almost real time allows quick reactions to events in the field.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry control allows engineers to intervene with assets such as pumps and by remotely switching pumps on or off depending on the circumstances.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry is used in complex systems such as missiles, RPVs, spacecraft, oil rigs, and chemical plants since it allows the automatic monitoring, alerting, and record-keeping necessary for efficient and safe operation.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Space agencies such as NASA, ISRO, the European Space Agency (ESA), and other agencies use telemetry and/or telecommand systems to collect data from spacecraft and satellites.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry is used in the development of missiles, satellites and aircraft because the system might be destroyed during or after the test.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Engineers need critical system parameters to analyze (and improve) the performance of the system.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In the absence of telemetry, this data would often be unavailable.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry is used by crewed or uncrewed spacecraft for data transmission.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Distances of more than 25.1 billion kilometers (May 2025) have been covered, e.g., by Voyager 1.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In rocketry, telemetry equipment forms an integral part of the rocket range assets used to monitor the position and health of a launch vehicle to determine range safety flight termination criteria (Range purpose is for public safety).
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Problems include the extreme environment (temperature, acceleration and vibration), the energy supply, antenna alignment and (at long distances, e.g., in spaceflight) signal travel time.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Today nearly every type of aircraft, missiles, or spacecraft carries a wireless telemetry system as it is tested.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Aeronautical mobile telemetry is used for the safety of the pilots and persons on the ground during flight tests.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry from an on-board flight test instrumentation system is the primary source of real-time measurement and status information transmitted during the testing of crewed and uncrewed aircraft.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Intercepted telemetry was an important source of intelligence for the United States and UK when Soviet missiles were tested; for this purpose, the United States operated a listening post in Iran.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Eventually, the Russians discovered the United States intelligence-gathering network and encrypted their missile-test telemetry signals.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry was also a source for the Soviets, who operated listening ships in Cardigan Bay to eavesdrop on UK missile tests performed in the area.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In factories, buildings and houses, energy consumption of systems such as HVAC are monitored at multiple locations; related parameters (e.g., temperature) are sent via wireless telemetry to a central location.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] The information is collected and processed, enabling the most efficient use of energy.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Such systems also facilitate predictive maintenance.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Many resources need to be distributed over wide areas.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry is useful in these cases, since it allows the logistics system to channel resources where they are needed, as well as provide security for those assets; principal examples of this are dry goods, fluids, and granular bulk solids.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] This facilitates knowledge of their location, and can record their status and disposition, as when merchandise with barcode labels is scanned through a checkout reader at point-of-sale systems in a retail store.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Stationary or hand-held barcode RFID scanners or Optical reader with remote communications, can be used to expedite inventory tracking and counting in stores, warehouses, shipping terminals, transportation carriers and factories.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Fluids stored in tanks are a principal object of constant commercial telemetry.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry is used to communicate the variable measurements of flow and tank level sensors detecting fluid movements and/or volumes by pneumatic, hydrostatic, or differential pressure; tank-confined ultrasonic, radar or Doppler effect echoes; or mechanical or magnetic sensors.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry of bulk solids is common for tracking and reporting the volume status and condition of grain and livestock feed bins, powdered or granular food, powders and pellets for manufacturing, sand and gravel, and other granular bulk solids.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] While technology associated with fluid tank monitoring also applies, in part, to granular bulk solids, reporting of overall container weight, or other gross characteristics and conditions, are sometimes required, owing to bulk solids' more complex and variable physical characteristics.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry is used for patients (biotelemetry) who are at risk of abnormal heart activity, generally in a coronary care unit.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry specialists are sometimes used to monitor many patients within a hospital.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Such patients are outfitted with measuring, recording and transmitting devices.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] A data log can be useful in diagnosis of the patient's condition by doctors.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] An alerting function can alert nurses if the patient is suffering from an acute (or dangerous) condition.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Systems are available in medical-surgical nursing for monitoring to rule out a heart condition, or to monitor a response to antiarrhythmic medications such as amiodarone.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] A new and emerging application for telemetry is in the field of neurophysiology, or neurotelemetry.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Neurophysiology is the study of the central and peripheral nervous systems through the recording of bioelectrical activity, whether spontaneous or stimulated.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In neurotelemetry (NT) the electroencephalogram (EEG) of a patient is monitored remotely by a registered EEG technologist using advanced communication software.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] The goal of neurotelemetry is to recognize a decline in a patient's condition before physical signs and symptoms are present.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Neurotelemetry is synonymous with real-time continuous video EEG monitoring and has application in the epilepsy monitoring unit, neuro ICU, pediatric ICU and newborn ICU.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Due to the labor-intensive nature of continuous EEG monitoring NT is typically done in the larger academic teaching hospitals using in-house programs that include R.EEG Technologists, IT support staff, neurologist and neurophysiologist and monitoring support personnel.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Modern microprocessor speeds, software algorithms and video data compression allow hospitals to centrally record and monitor continuous digital EEGs of multiple critically ill patients simultaneously.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Neurotelemetry and continuous EEG monitoring provides dynamic information about brain function that permits early detection of changes in neurologic status, which is especially useful when the clinical examination is limited.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry is used to study wildlife, and has been useful for monitoring threatened species at the individual level.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Animals under study can be outfitted with instrumentation tags, which include sensors that measure temperature, diving depth and duration (for marine animals), speed and location (using GPS or Argos packages).
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry tags can give researchers information about animal behavior, functions, and their environment.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] This information is then either stored (with archival tags) or the tags can send (or transmit) their information to a satellite or handheld receiving device.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Capturing and marking wild animals can put them at some risk, so it is important to minimize these impacts.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] At a 2005 workshop in Las Vegas, a seminar noted the introduction of telemetry equipment which would allow vending machines to communicate sales and inventory data to a route truck or to a headquarters.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] This data could be used for a variety of purposes, such as eliminating the need for drivers to make a first trip to see which items needed to be restocked before delivering the inventory.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Retailers also use RFID tags to track inventory and prevent shoplifting.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Most of these tags passively respond to RFID readers (e.g., at the cashier), but active RFID tags are available which periodically transmit location information to a base station.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] A telemetry-based Tracking system is useful for tracking persons and property in law enforcement.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] An ankle collar worn by convicts on probation can warn authorities if a person violates the terms of his or her parole, such as by straying from authorized boundaries or visiting an unauthorized location.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry has also enabled bait cars, where law enforcement can rig a car with cameras and tracking equipment and leave it somewhere they expect it to be stolen.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] When stolen the telemetry equipment reports the location of the vehicle, enabling a Stolen vehicle recovery process where law enforcement can deactivate the engine and lock the doors when it is stopped by responding officers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In some countries, telemetry is used to measure the amount of electrical energy consumed.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] The electricity meter communicates with a concentrator, and the latter sends the information through GPRS or GSM to the energy provider's server.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry is also used for the remote monitoring of substations and their equipment.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] For data transmission, phase line carrier systems operating on frequencies between 30 and 400 kHz are sometimes used.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In falconry, "telemetry" means a small radio transmitter carried by a bird of prey that will allow the bird's owner to track it when it is out of sight.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry is used in testing hostile environments which are dangerous to humans.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Examples include munitions storage facilities, radioactive sites, volcanoes, deep sea, and outer space.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Telemetry is used in many battery operated wireless systems to inform monitoring personnel when the battery power is reaching a low point and the end item needs fresh batteries.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In the mining industry, telemetry serves two main purposes: the measurement of key parameters from mining equipment and the monitoring of safety practices.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] The information provided by the collection and analysis of key parameters allows for root-cause identification of inefficient operations, unsafe practices and incorrect equipment usage for maximizing productivity and safety.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Further applications of the technology allow for sharing knowledge and best practices across the organization.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In software, telemetry is used to gather data on the use and performance of applications and application components, e.g. how often certain features are used, measurements of start-up time and processing time, hardware, application crashes, and general usage statistics and/or user behavior.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] In some cases, very detailed data is reported like individual window metrics, counts of used features, and individual function timings.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] This kind of telemetry can be useful to software developers to receive data from a wide variety of endpoints that can't possibly all be tested in-house, as well as getting data on the popularity of certain features and whether they should be given priority or be considered for removal.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] Due to concerns about privacy since software telemetry can easily be used to profile users, telemetry in user software is often user choice, commonly presented as an opt-out feature (requiring explicit user action to disable it) or user choice during the software installation process.
[src:gnmi-protocol/telemetry] As in other telecommunications fields, international standards exist for telemetry equipment and software.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] YANG enables comprehensive network automation by providing a standardized way to model the configuration and state data of network elements.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] The language can be used to define the format of event notifications emitted by network devices and allows data modelers to define the signature of RPCs that can be invoked on network elements via the NETCONF protocol.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] Being protocol-independent, YANG models can be converted into various encoding formats, including XML, JSON, and CBOR, depending on the network configuration protocol's support.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] YANG is a modular language and represents data structures in a hierarchical tree format.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] It includes numerous built-in data types, with the capability for users to derive additional application-specific types.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] More complex reusable data structures can be represented as "groupings," which promote model reusability and consistency.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] YANG data models can use XPath expressions to define constraints on the elements of a YANG data model, enabling validation of configuration data before it is committed to devices.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] YANG has become the de facto standard for modeling network device configurations across the telecommunications industry and is widely supported by major network equipment manufacturers.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] It plays a crucial role in software-defined networking (SDN) and network function virtualization (NFV) environments by providing a consistent interface for programmatic network management.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] Many network management protocols have associated data modeling languages.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] The first widely deployed Internet standard for network management was the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] The data modeling language associated with SNMP was called the Structure of Management Information (SMI).
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] The SMI language itself was based on the 1988 version of the Abstract Syntax Notation One (ASN.1).
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] The current version of the SMI language, SMIv2 defined in RFC 2578, 2579 and 2580, has developed into an extended subset of ASN.1.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] In the late 1990s, a project was started to create a replacement for SMIv2, which was called SMIng.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] One motivation was to decouple SMIng from the management protocol SNMP and to give SMIng a syntactic structure that is both easy to parse for computer programs and easy to learn for people familiar with programming languages that use a C-like notation.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] While the SMIng project did not succeed in the IETF, the SMIng specifications were published as experimental documents in May 2004 (RFC 3780, 3781).
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] Soon after the development of the NETCONF protocol in the IETF, it became clear that a data modeling language was needed to define data models manipulated by the NETCONF protocol.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] A design team created a proposal that became the basis of the YANG language.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] The syntactic structure and the base type system was essentially borrowed from SMIng.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] However, based on the lessons learned from the SMIng project, no attempts were made to make the YANG protocol neutral.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] Instead, YANG ties into concepts of the NETCONF protocol, such as the assumption that data model instances can be serialized into XML.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] Standardization of YANG started with the formation of the NETMOD working group in April 2008.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] The YANG 1.0 specification was published as RFC 6020 in October 2010.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] Recently, the NETMOD working group has been working on YANG 1.1, which has been published in August 2016 in RFC 7950.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] The following YANG module `example-sports` shows a data model for team sports.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] The module declares a namespace and a prefix and imports the type library module `ietf-yang-types` before defining the type `season`.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] It then defines a container `sports` that includes a list of `person`s and a list of `team`s.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] A team has a list of players that reference persons via the `leafref` type and its `path` restriction.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] The code block below shows the JSON representation of an instantiation of the `example-sports` data model.
[src:gnmi-protocol/yang] The code block below shows the XML representation of an instantiation of the `example-sports` data model.
